<DOC><DOCNO> AP891104-0110 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-11-04-89 1822EST</FILEID><FIRST>r a AM-WeatherpageWeather     11-04 0271</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0280</SECOND><HEAD>Snow and Gusty Winds Whip Through Rockies</HEAD><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   Blustery winds swept the eastern slopes of the Rockies inWyoming and Colorado on Saturday and roads were closed atYellowstone National Park, which was hit with 5 inches of snow.   Wind gusts of up to 60 mph were reported west of Fort Collins,Colo., and winds gusted to 65 mph near Vedauwoo, Wyo.   A high wind warning was in effect Saturday night forsoutheastern Wyoming. A high wind watch was posted for the frontrange and northeast plains of Colorado.   An advisory for snow and blowing snow was in effect Saturdaynight for the northern mountains of Wyoming and the centralmountains of Colorado. Up to 5 inches of snow blanketed theYellowstone National Park area, closing many roads.   Winds at Idaho Falls, Idaho, gusted to 48 mph. Strong winds alsowere whipping through the Columbia Basin of eastern Oregon, withgusts of 48 mph reported at Pendleton.   An upper level weather disturbance moving out of Montana intoWyoming was responsible for the snow and gusty winds.   Showers were scattered from Washington and Oregon to MinnesotaSaturday morning and early afternoon. Skies were sunny across muchof the southern half of the nation.   Strong southerly winds kept temperatures warm into the 50s and60s in the Great Plains and middle Mississippi Valley, and in the60s and 70s in the southern Plains.   Temperatures reached the 70s and 80s in southern Arizona andsouthern California, and across Florida. Temperatures were in the30s in the upper Mississippi Valley, the upper Great Lakes andnorthern New England.</TEXT></DOC>